it would be good to create a new custom field (user picker) and be able to update this field with the value of the logged user in a transition's postfunction.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8226].
  {panel}

Please see attached screenshos. The user picker is a little bit too small (see the filter button).

It's related to the language used. When using danish, not all of the filter button is seen. When using english, you can see a little more.

When the Wiki renderer is enabled, text like $\{JAVA_HOME} in existing fields and comments breaks with:

Unknown macro: \{JAVA_HOME}

We should fix the renderer to print literally 'macros' that it doesn't understand.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8217].
  {panel}

Doing support frequently involves asking people to perform a sequence of steps (check this, check that, ...). Often the response as to whether all these steps has been followed is ambiguous ("It still doesn't work"). It would be interesting if we could embed {tasklist} macros in comments, as a means of highlighting things that need confirmation, and getting a definite response on those things.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8209].
  {panel}

In JIRA, users often have to edit files like conf/server.xml and entityengine.xml.  Currently these files are saved with UNIX linefeeds even in the ZIP distribution, which means they cannot be edited with notepad (the default editor on XP).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-8190].
  {panel}

How about shipping a {{\{stacktrace}}} macro or something similar with JIRA? {{\{code}}} works fine, but it would be nice to have an easy way to print a nicely formatted, colorful stacktrace.
